<!-- SECTION 1 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">The analytical gap</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">The index tells you the scale. It cannot tell you who bears it.</h2>

<p class="prose">The UNCTAD Strait of Hormuz Dashboard, launched 28 April 2026, aggregates the market signal clearly. The Baltic Dirty Tanker Index stands at 2,795, against a 2024 average of 1,091. VLSFO bunker in Singapore has risen from a 2024 average of $571 per tonne to $1,076. Brent crude has traded above $120 on intraday peaks. These are the right numbers to watch. They confirm severity. They cannot tell you who is exposed.</p>

<p class="prose">An accumulation underwriter pricing a P&I book, a crude desk managing a supply position, or a lender stress-testing a fleet facility needs something the index cannot provide: which specific counterparties carry Hormuz exposure, for which commodity, at what percentage of their total seaborne supply, and whether any credible alternative supply source exists and at what cost. Run it through The Narrows before you price it. The bilateral dependency matrix, the resupply cost analysis, and the Plan B assessment are what the index cannot give you — and what every serious counterparty needs before the political situation resolves.</p>

<hr class="section-rule" />

<!-- SECTION 2 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">The geography</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">Hormuz is a cul de sac. There is no Cape option.</h2>

<p class="prose">The Persian Gulf has one navigable exit: the Strait of Hormuz. Everything that loads in the Gulf — crude petroleum from Saudi Arabia, UAE, Kuwait, and Iraq; LNG from Qatar; bulk commodities from Gulf ports — must transit a 33-kilometre channel to reach open water. If that channel closes, nothing moves in or out. Not crude. Not LNG. Not bulk. The Cape of Good Hope is irrelevant. A vessel that cannot exit the Gulf cannot route anywhere.</p>

<p class="prose">This makes Hormuz categorically different from other major risk corridors. At Malacca, Lombok and Sunda provide partial bypass capacity. At Suez, the Cape is a painful but navigable alternative. At Hormuz, there is no equivalent. The capacity sensitivity score in the Narrows model is 1.00, meaning every percentage point of stated disruption translates directly to commercial impact with no bypass absorption whatsoever.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">The correct framing</div>
  <div class="callout-body">Hormuz is not a rerouting problem. It is a supply halt. For LNG carriers, for crude tankers, for bulk vessels — the constraint is identical. If Hormuz closes, Gulf cargo does not move. <strong>The analytical question is not what rerouting costs. It is what bilateral exposure looks like and what alternative supply sources exist and at what price.</strong> Run it through The Narrows to get both answers.</div>
</div>

<hr class="section-rule" />

