<!-- SECTION 4 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">The toll question</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">Paying is not a commercial decision. It is a political one.</h2>

<p class="prose">Iran's toll of over $1 million per vessel created a situation the maritime industry has not faced at scale before. Vessels at anchor in the Gulf face a real economic calculation: the daily cost of sitting still — bunker consumption at idle, charter rate continuing to accrue, demurrage building against the cargo — versus the toll cost of moving. At some point, paying becomes cheaper than waiting. That threshold is calculable and The Narrows can model it.</p>

<p class="prose">But framing the toll as a commercial decision understates what is actually happening. Paying Iran's toll is a political act. It legitimises the principle that a state can charge passage through an international strait. It sets a precedent that every other littoral state with a chokepoint in its waters has already noted. It may expose the paying party to sanctions risk depending on jurisdiction and counterparty. And it funds the enforcement capacity that makes the next toll more credible.</p>

<div class="callout-red">
  <div class="callout-label">The freedom of navigation principle</div>
  <div class="callout-body">International maritime law, specifically UNCLOS Article 38, guarantees the right of transit passage through international straits used for international navigation. Hormuz qualifies. Iran's toll is a direct challenge to that principle. <strong>The commercially rational response — pay the toll and move — is also the response that most rapidly erodes the legal framework that protects every other international strait.</strong> This is not a risk that appears in any freight index. It is exactly the kind of structural exposure that requires bilateral analysis, not market data.</div>
</div>

<p class="prose">The correct framing for risk professionals is not "what toll level makes compliance rational." It is: if freedom of navigation principles hold and the political situation eventually resolves, how long can my counterparties sustain the disruption before their supply chains require a structural response? And what does that structural response cost? That is the Plan B question, and it is where the analysis becomes actionable.</p>

<hr class="section-rule" />

<!-- SECTION 5 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">The Plan B question</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">If Gulf supply is unavailable, what are the alternatives and what do they cost?</h2>

<p class="prose">The dependency matrix shows what is at risk. The more operationally useful question is what happens next: for each major importer, are there alternative supply sources, can they scale to cover the gap, and what is the cost differential? This is where bilateral trade analysis moves from exposure measurement to decision support.</p>

<p class="prose">The answers vary significantly by commodity and importer, and some of the most interesting stories are not the obvious ones.</p>

<div class="plan-b-grid">
  <div class="plan-b-card">
    <div class="plan-b-label">Japan — crude petroleum</div>
    <div class="plan-b-title">84% Hormuz dependent. Partial alternatives exist at cost.</div>
    <p class="plan-b-body">Japan's non-Gulf crude supply comes primarily from Russia (now sanctioned for most buyers), West Africa, and North Sea producers. None of these sources can replace Gulf volume at scale in the short term. Spot procurement from West African producers adds approximately $4–6 per barrel in additional freight cost on longer voyages. Strategic petroleum reserves provide approximately 150 days of buffer at current consumption rates. The 30-day VaR of $6.1B understates the structural adjustment cost of a prolonged closure.</p>
    <div class="plan-b-stat">Non-Gulf alternatives: partial · Freight premium: $4–6/bbl · SPR buffer: ~150 days</div>
  </div>
  <div class="plan-b-card">
    <div class="plan-b-label">India — LNG</div>
    <div class="plan-b-title">48% Hormuz dependent for LNG. US and Australian supply can partially compensate.</div>
    <p class="plan-b-body">India's LNG dependency on Hormuz is the highest of any major importer at 48%. Unlike crude, LNG has genuine alternative supply sources: US LNG exports via the Atlantic, Australian LNG via different corridors entirely. The constraint is terminal capacity and spot market availability, not the existence of non-Gulf supply. A sustained Hormuz closure would accelerate India's already active diversification toward US and Australian LNG — but at a freight premium and with a lag measured in months, not days.</p>
    <div class="plan-b-stat">US / Australian LNG available · Freight premium significant · Diversification timeline: months</div>
  </div>
  <div class="plan-b-card">
    <div class="plan-b-label">South Korea — crude petroleum</div>
    <div class="plan-b-title">72% Hormuz dependent. Among the most structurally exposed buyers.</div>
    <p class="plan-b-body">South Korea has fewer non-Gulf crude alternatives than Japan and less domestic storage buffer. Its refinery configuration is also optimised for Gulf crudes, meaning that switching grades adds operational cost and potentially reduces output efficiency. The combination of high dependency, limited alternatives, and refinery inflexibility makes South Korea one of the most acutely exposed bilateral counterparties in the Narrows matrix. A 30-day disruption VaR of $3.5B for crude alone understates the true cost of adjustment.</p>
    <div class="plan-b-stat">Limited non-Gulf alternatives · Refinery grade constraints · 30d VaR: $3.5B crude only</div>
  </div>
  <div class="plan-b-card">
    <div class="plan-b-label">Qatar — LNG exports</div>
    <div class="plan-b-title">100% Hormuz dependent. No export route exists.</div>
    <p class="plan-b-body">Qatar is the world's largest LNG exporter and its entire export capacity exits via Hormuz. There is no pipeline alternative, no overland route, and no other maritime exit from the Gulf. A Hormuz closure does not disrupt Qatar's LNG exports. It stops them entirely. Every long-term LNG supply contract Qatar holds becomes undeliverable for the duration of the closure. The counterparty risk embedded in those contracts is not a freight cost question. It is a force majeure and contract law question.</p>
    <div class="plan-b-stat">Export dependency: 100% · Alternative exit: none · Contract status: force majeure</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">What The Narrows surfaces that market data cannot</div>
  <div class="callout-body">The bilateral dependency matrix identifies who is exposed. The Plan B analysis identifies whether alternatives exist and at what cost. Neither question is answerable from freight indices or aggregate throughput data. <strong>The combination tells you which counterparties can absorb a sustained Hormuz disruption and which cannot — and that is the underwriting, lending, and trading question that actually matters.</strong></div>
</div>

<hr class="section-rule" />

<!-- SECTION 6 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">The conclusion</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">Political resolution is the only real answer. Map your Plan B while you wait for it.</h2>

<p class="prose">The economic pressure to pay Iran's toll is real. The vessels at anchor in the Gulf are losing money every day. But the structural response — paying, normalising, and waiting for the market to adjust — is also the response that most rapidly makes the next Hormuz toll, and the next Indonesia toll proposal, and the next strait monetisation attempt, more credible and more likely.</p>

<p class="prose">The correct response to a challenge to freedom of navigation is to let the political and legal process work, support the vessels and counterparties bearing the cost of non-compliance, and use the time to understand and price the bilateral exposure properly. That means knowing, before the disruption not during it, what percentage of each counterparty's supply transits Hormuz, whether credible Plan B supply sources exist, and what the cost of switching to them looks like.</p>

<p class="prose">The Narrows does not tell you how to resolve the Hormuz situation. No model can. What it tells you is what your specific exposure looks like, what your counterparties' alternatives are, and what a credible Plan B costs. That is the analysis that should precede every underwriting decision, every credit facility, and every trading position with Hormuz exposure. Run it through The Narrows before the next disruption, not during it.</p>

<div class="method-note">
  <div class="method-note-label">Methodology and data sources</div>
  <div class="method-note-body">Bilateral dependency figures derived from the Narrows Chokepoint Dependency Simulation Model. Primary data source: UN Comtrade 2023 bilateral import data via Comtrade v3 public API, covering LNG (HS 271111), crude petroleum (HS 2709), and refined petroleum (HS 2710). Data quality: Tier 1 bilateral data for 10 of 11 EU reporters and all major non-EU importers. France remains at Tier 3 world aggregate pending 2023 Comtrade submission. Capacity sensitivity score of 1.00 for Hormuz reflects the absence of any navigable alternative for vessels exiting the Persian Gulf. Market rate figures: VLSFO Singapore $1,076 per tonne; BDTI 2,795 (LSEG Data &amp; Analytics via UNCTAD Hormuz Dashboard, April 2026). Plan B freight premium estimates are indicative ranges based on publicly available spot market data and voyage economics. SPR buffer estimate based on IEA Japan strategic reserve data. All model assumptions are substitutable. 22 chokepoints modelled.</div>
</div>

